      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 id="fescue">Tall Fescue</h2>

    <p>Tall Fescue thrives in fall and spring, goes semi-dormant and stressed through summer heat, and doesn&rsquo;t tolerate nitrogen push during July and August. The most important feed of the entire year is <strong>fall</strong> &mdash; not spring. Most homeowners over-fertilize Fescue in spring and under-fertilize in fall. The reverse is what actually works.</p>

    <div class="grass-section">
      <div class="grass-header">
        <div>
          <div class="grass-name">Tall Fescue</div>
          <div class="grass-tagline">2&ndash;4 applications/year &middot; Fall is the priority season &middot; Never fertilize in summer heat</div>
        </div>
        <span class="grass-badge badge-cool">Cool-Season</span>
      </div>
      <table class="schedule-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Month</th><th>Action</th><th>Product / Notes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">Jan&ndash;Feb</td><td class="sched-skip">Skip</td><td>Dormant or very slow growth. No fertilizer. Apply pre-emergent for winter annuals if not done in fall.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">March</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; Light Spring</td><td>Optional light application (0.5 lb N/1,000 sq ft) as soil hits 50&deg;F. Slow-release only. Less is more here &mdash; you&rsquo;re waking the lawn, not pushing it.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">April</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; Spring Feed</td><td>Balanced fertilizer before temps climb above 80&deg;F daytime. Andersons PGF 16-4-8 at full rate. Last nitrogen push before summer &mdash; make it count.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">May&ndash;Aug</td><td class="sched-skip">Skip</td><td>No synthetic nitrogen during summer heat. If color fades badly, apply Milorganite at half-rate only during cooler stretches (under 85&deg;F highs).</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">September</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; #1 Feed of Year</td><td>As temps cool below 80&deg;F, apply 1 lb N/1,000 sq ft. Feeds recovery from summer stress. Pair with core aeration and overseeding for maximum impact.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">October</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; Second Fall Feed</td><td>Apply balanced or potassium-heavy fertilizer. Builds root mass before winter dormancy. 1 lb N/1,000 sq ft.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">Nov&ndash;Dec</td><td class="sched-skip">Wrap Up</td><td>Optional &ldquo;winterizer&rdquo; in early November if still actively growing. Use slow-release low-N/high-K formula. Skip if ground is already hard.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <div class="grass-footer">
