    <h2 id="zoysia">Zoysia</h2>

    <p>Zoysia is a slow-growing, dense warm-season grass. It has a shorter active season than Bermuda and is more sensitive to late-season nitrogen. It also takes longer to green up in spring &mdash; don&rsquo;t get impatient and fertilize too early.</p>

    <div class="grass-section">
      <div class="grass-header">
        <div>
          <div class="grass-name">Zoysia</div>
          <div class="grass-tagline">3&ndash;4 applications/year &middot; Slower spring green-up &middot; Hard stop at Labor Day</div>
        </div>
        <span class="grass-badge badge-warm">Warm-Season</span>
      </div>
      <table class="schedule-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Month</th><th>Action</th><th>Product / Notes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">Jan&ndash;Apr</td><td class="sched-skip">Skip</td><td>Dormant. Do not fertilize. Apply pre-emergent (Prodiamine) when soil hits 50&ndash;55&deg;F &mdash; typically late February to early April depending on zone.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">May</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; First Feed</td><td>Wait for consistent 65&deg;F soil temp. Apply balanced fertilizer (16-4-8). 0.5 lb N/1,000 sq ft. Patience here prevents pushing weeds instead of grass.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">June&ndash;July</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; Peak Season</td><td>One application per month during active growth. 0.75&ndash;1 lb N/1,000 sq ft. Scotts Southern or Milorganite both work. Avoid pushing excessive nitrogen &mdash; Zoysia doesn&rsquo;t need it like Bermuda does.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">August</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; Final Summer</td><td>Last nitrogen application for the season. Apply by mid-August maximum. Use balanced formula &mdash; not high-N only at this stage.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">Sep&ndash;Dec</td><td class="sched-skip">Skip</td><td>No nitrogen after Labor Day. Zoysia is very susceptible to winter kill from late-season soft growth. Potassium-only applications acceptable in early September.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <div class="grass-footer">
        <div class="grass-footer-product">
          <strong>Top Pick: Scotts Southern Lawn Food (32-0-10)</strong>
          <span>High N with potassium support for warm-season density &middot; ~$28+</span>
