      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 id="staugustine">St. Augustine</h2>

    <p>St. Augustine is dominant in the Gulf Coast, Florida, and deep South (USDA zones 8&ndash;10). It has one unique fertilizer concern: extreme sensitivity to <strong>iron deficiency</strong>, which shows up as yellow-green color even when nitrogen levels are adequate. An iron supplement in summer can solve what more nitrogen never will.</p>

    <div class="grass-section">
      <div class="grass-header">
        <div>
          <div class="grass-name">St. Augustine</div>
          <div class="grass-tagline">4&ndash;6 applications/year &middot; Iron-sensitive &middot; Near year-round in zones 9&ndash;10</div>
        </div>
        <span class="grass-badge badge-warm">Warm-Season</span>
      </div>
      <table class="schedule-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Month</th><th>Action</th><th>Product / Notes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">Jan&ndash;Feb</td><td class="sched-skip">Skip / Minimal</td><td>Zones 8&ndash;9: skip. Zone 10 with year-round growth: light slow-release is acceptable. No quick-release nitrogen in winter.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">March</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; First Feed</td><td>When soil hits 65&deg;F. Apply balanced fertilizer at 1 lb N/1,000 sq ft. Add iron supplement if color is pale green &mdash; iron chlorosis is common in early spring.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">Apr&ndash;May</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; Active Feed</td><td>Every 6&ndash;8 weeks during peak growth. Milorganite (includes iron) or balanced granular. Watch for chinch bugs &mdash; peak damage season.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">Jun&ndash;Jul</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; Summer Feed</td><td>Continue slow-release during heat. Add chelated iron if yellowing appears (common in alkaline soils). Do not apply quick-release N when temps are above 90&deg;F.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">August</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; Late Summer</td><td>Apply balanced fertilizer. Last heavy nitrogen push before fall slowdown in most zones.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">September</td><td class="sched-skip">Taper Off</td><td>Light application only in Zone 9&ndash;10. Zone 8: stop nitrogen completely. Potassium supplement acceptable to harden for winter.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">Oct&ndash;Dec</td><td class="sched-skip">Skip</td><td>No nitrogen in Zones 8&ndash;9. Zone 10 may continue light slow-release through mild winters only.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <div class="grass-footer">
        <div class="grass-footer-product">
          <strong>Top Pick: Milorganite Organic Nitrogen 6-4-0 (32 lb)</strong>
          <span>Contains iron &mdash; addresses St. Augustine&rsquo;s #1 deficiency &middot; ~$30+</span>
        </div>
        <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B08TM3ZCVL?tag=lawnunlocked-20" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="btn-amz">&#128722; Amazon</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 id="bluegrass">Kentucky Bluegrass</h2>

    <p>Kentucky Bluegrass is the premium cool-season grass &mdash; dense and beautiful in its season, but demanding. Like Fescue, its prime growing periods are spring and fall. It&rsquo;s more susceptible to summer patch disease than Fescue under nitrogen push, and it tends to thin badly if over-fertilized the previous spring.</p>

    <div class="grass-section">
      <div class="grass-header">
        <div>
          <div class="grass-name">Kentucky Bluegrass</div>
          <div class="grass-tagline">3&ndash;5 applications/year &middot; Fall is critical &middot; Summer nitrogen causes disease</div>
        </div>
        <span class="grass-badge badge-cool">Cool-Season</span>
      </div>
      <table class="schedule-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Month</th><th>Action</th><th>Product / Notes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">Jan&ndash;Feb</td><td class="sched-skip">Skip</td><td>Dormant. No fertilizer. Apply pre-emergent for crabgrass in late February as soil approaches 50&deg;F.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">Mar&ndash;Apr</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; Spring Feed</td><td>Apply 0.5&ndash;1 lb N/1,000 sq ft as growth begins. Use slow-release to avoid flush growth that leads to summer burnout and disease. Andersons PGF 16-4-8 is ideal.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">May</td><td class="sched-skip">Optional Light</td><td>Light potassium-only application to support summer stress tolerance. Avoid heavy nitrogen &mdash; heat season is approaching.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">Jun&ndash;Aug</td><td class="sched-skip">Skip</td><td>No synthetic nitrogen during summer. Bluegrass is prone to summer patch disease when pushed with nitrogen during heat. Irrigate deeply instead of feeding.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">September</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; Most Important</td><td>The year&rsquo;s most critical application. 1 lb N/1,000 sq ft as temps drop below 80&deg;F. Core aerate first if you can. Seed thin areas immediately after.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">October</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; Second Fall Feed</td><td>Apply balanced or high-K fertilizer. Builds root mass before dormancy. Critical for winter survival and strong early spring green-up.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">November</td><td class="sched-action">&#10003; Winterizer</td><td>Optional late-season application before hard freeze. Use high-potassium formula to boost cold hardiness. Skip if temps already below 40&deg;F consistently.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="sched-month">December</td><td class="sched-skip">Skip</td><td>Dormant. No fertilizer.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
